{
  "texts": [
    "For part 1, that h g is a function from A g to A ′ g, i.e., sending proper filters from A to proper filters from A ′, follows from the definition of h g and the fact that h is a homomorphism.",
    "Where A g = ⟨S, ⊑, {R i } i∈I, P g ⟩ and A ′ g = ⟨S ′, ⊑ ′, {R ′ i } i∈I, P ′ g ⟩, we will show that for all proper filters X, Y from A and Y ′ from A ′:• if Y ⊑ X, then h g (Y) ⊑ ′ h g (X) (⊑-forth); • if Y ′ ⊑ ′ h g (X), then ∃Y: Y ⊑ X and h g (Y) = Y ′ (p-⊑-back); • if XR i Y, then h g (X)R ′ i h g (Y) (R-forth); • if h g (X)R ′ i Y ′, then ∃Y: XR i Y and h g (Y) = Y ′ (p-R-back); • ∀X ′ ∈ P ′ g, h -1 g [X ′] ∈ P g (pull back).",
    "For ⊑-forth, if Y ⊑ X, so Y ⊇ X, then h g (Y) = h -1 [Y] ⊇ h -1 [X] = h g (X), so h g (Y) ⊑ ′ h g (X).",
    "For ⊑-back, suppose Y ′ ⊑ ′ h g (X), so Y ′ ⊇ h g (X).",
    "We claim [h[Y ′] ∪ X) is a proper filter."
  ]
}